{{lowercasetitle}} The [[Bayer designation]] '''f Eridani''' (f Eri / f Eridani) is shared by two [[star]]s in the [[constellation]] [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]]. They share a single [[Hipparcos]] catalogue entry, HIP 17797, but have separate [[Bright Star Catalogue]] listings, HR 1189 and 1190: *[[HD 24071]] (HR 1189) *[[HD 24072]] (HR 1190)
{{SIA |astronomical objects}}
[[Category:Bayer objects|Eridani, f]] [[Category:Eridanus (constellation)]]

{{unreferenced|date=July 2009}}

'''Forbon''' is a [[Vulcanized fibre|vulcanized fiber]] that was created in the early 1900s by the [[National Vulcanized Fiber|NVF]] company. It was used on the original [[Pickup (music technology)|pickups]] that [[Leo Fender]] (founder of [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender Guitars]]) created for the [[Fender Stratocaster|Stratocaster]], [[Fender Telecaster|Telecaster]], and the [[Fender Precision Bass|Precision Bass]]. It is still used on reissue [[Electric guitar|guitar]] and [[Bass guitar|bass]] models from that era. Lollar Pickups and The [[Seymour Duncan]] Pickup Company also use Forbon on many of their pickups, such as early Fender style replacement pickups. Forbon is still sold by the NVF company.

[[Category:Fibers]]
[[Category:Guitars]]

{{manufacturing-stub}}

{{No footnotes|date=September 2015}}
{{Italic title}}
[[Image:HANZAB V5 cover.jpg|thumb|right|HANZAB Volume 5]]
The '''''Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds''''', known as '''''HANZAB''''', is the pre-eminent scientific reference on [[birds]] in the region, which includes [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Antarctica]], and [[Southern Ocean|the surrounding ocean]] and [[subantarctic]] islands. It attempts to collate all that is known about each of the [[List of Australasian birds|957 species recorded]].

''HANZAB'' is the largest project ever undertaken by the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] (RAOU), also known as Birds Australia. It was prepared over 20 years by teams of full and part-time writers, editors and artists, and published by [[Oxford University Press]] in seven volumes between 1990 and 2006 (volumes 1 and 7 each in two parts).

== Contents of each volume ==

# Ratites to Ducks (in two parts) (1990)
# Raptors to Lapwings (1993)
# Snipe to Pigeons (1996)
# Parrots to Dollarbird (1999)
# Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats (2001)
# Pardalotes to Shrike-thrushes (2002)
# Boatbill to Starlings (in two parts) (2006)

